In all previous cases the increase in the range of the

pairwise entanglement means that all pairs at distances

smaller than R share a ﬁnite amount of entanglement ͑as

quantiﬁed by the concurrence͒. There are one-

dimensional spin systems where the pairwise entangle-

ment has qualitative different features as a function of

the distance between sites. An example is the long-

distance entanglement observed by Campos Venuti, De-

gli Esposti Buschi, and Roncaglia ͑2006͒. Given a mea-

sure of entanglement E͑␳ij͒, Campos Venuti, Degli Esposti Buschi, and Roncaglia showed that it is possible

that E͑␳ij͒ 0 when ͉i − j͉ → ϱ in the ground state. Longdistance entanglement can be realized in various one-

dimensional models as in the dimerized frustrated

Heisenberg models or in the AKLT model. For these

two models the entanglement is highly nonuniform and

it is mainly concentrated in the end-to-end pair of the

chain.

Spontaneous symmetry breaking can inﬂuence the en-

tanglement in the ground state. To see this, it is conve-

nient to introduce the thermal ground state ␳0

=

